sql:
SELECT MAX(version_number) 
FROM code_file_versions
WHERE file_id = 0;

external_knowledge:
- 'Trees' and 'branches' are metaphors for code files and functions, respectively;
- 'Complexity' refers to the cyclomatic complexity of the functions;
- 'Threshold' is set to an average cyclomatic complexity greater than 1.0;
- 'Unique trees' implies the number of unique functions in each code file.

- Preprocessor directives in C include `#include`, `#ifdef`, `#endif`, `#define`, and `#undef`;
- The file size is measured in bytes;
- Comments in code files are used to explain code and are often a measure of code readability and maintainability.

- "More complex" refers to files with an average code complexity greater than 50;
- "Updated" refers to files with a version number greater than 1;
- "Relatively large" refers to files with a size greater than 10,000 bytes.

- "Highly complex" refers to `code_complexity` > 50;
- "Highly readable" refers to `code_readability` > 60;
- "Significant number of internal or const variables" refers to `ninternal` > 50 or `nconst` > 20;
- "Not been accessed" refers to `access_count` being NULL;
- "Accessed more than 10 times" refers to `access_count` > 10.

- 'Blossoms' refers to code files;
- 'More than one function' means the file contains at least two functions;
- 'Average line length longer than 20' means the mean length of the lines in the file is greater than 20 characters.

- 'More complex code files' refers to files with more than one function and more than 1000 characters;
- 'Moderate number of unique characters' means the number of unique characters is between 1000 and 5000 inclusive;
- 'Code complexity' is a composite metric that combines multiple measures of code complexity.

- 'code files' are digital documents containing source code;
- 'seeds of variables' are identifiers of type 'variable' in the code files;
- 'average number of bytes' is the mean file size of all code files in the database.

- "Most recently uploaded" refers to the file with the latest upload date;
- "Largest" refers to the file with the greatest size in bytes;
- "Latest version" refers to the version with the most recent version date;
- "Largest entity" refers to the entity with the greatest size in bytes within the file.

sql:
SELECT file_id
FROM code_structure
WHERE ninternal = (SELECT MAX(ninternal) FROM code_structure);

external_knowledge:
- "Gardeners" refer to users in the code management system;
- "Plots" refer to code files;
- "Tended to the most plots" means the users who have accessed the most files;
- "Pruned" refers to edit actions;
- "Observed" refers to view actions;
- "Complexity of the plots" refers to the code complexity and cyclomatic complexity metrics.

- "Top 10" refers to the highest ranked files based on the average number of characters;
- "Variables" include internal, const, and enum variables;
- "More than 500 characters and 50 lines on average" means the average number of characters per file is greater than 500 and the average number of lines per file is greater than 50.

- 'More complex nested statements' refers to functions where the minimum statement nesting level is greater than 1;
- 'High comment density' refers to a comment ratio greater than 0.5;
- 'Length of the comments' refers to the number of characters in the comments.

sql:
SELECT file_name, file_size
FROM code_files
ORDER BY file_size DESC;
